==English==

===Etymology===
Old English ''[[godspel]]'' (corresponding to ''[[good]]'' + ''[[spell]]'', i.e. ‘good tidings’, the first element later associated with Old English ''[[god#Old English|god]]'' ‘God’), used to translate ecclesiastical Latin ''[[bona]] [[annuntiatio]]'', itself a translation of ecclesiastical Latin ''[[evangelium]]'', Greek ''[[εὐαγγέλιον]]'' ‘evangel’, literally ‘good news’.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The first section of the Christian scripture, comprising the books of [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]], [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]], [[Gospel of Luke|
Luke]] and [[Gospel of John|John]], concerned with the life, death, and teachings of Jesus.
# An account of the life, death, and teachings of Jesus, generally written during the first several centuries of the Common Era. 
# A message expected to have positive reception or effect.

